[asy]
unitsize(0.6inch);
pair A,B,C,G,M;
A = (0,0);
B = (2,0);
C = dir(120);
M = (B + C)/2;
G = (A + M)/3;
draw(Circle((A+B)/2,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
dot("$A$",A,SW);
dot("$B$",B,SE);
dot("$C$",C,N);
dot("$G$",G,NE);
dot("$M$",M,S);
[/asy]

As $C$ moves around the circle, $M$ moves around a circle with diameter $AB = 24$, and $G$ moves around a circle with radius $\frac{2}{3} \cdot 12 = 8$.  The area of this circle is $\pi (8^2) = 64 \pi$.  Since $G$ does not take on the positions corresponding to $A$ and $B$, the area of the region is $64 \pi - 2 \cdot \frac{1}{6} \pi (8^2) = 32 \pi$.  This is approximately $32 \cdot 3.14 \approx 100.48$.  To the nearest positive integer, the area is $\boxed{100}$.

